{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649669"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:06:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:06:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18370"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18370"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.25,0.4,0.05,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11088"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80759"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11088"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18370"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66061"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7465"},{"type":"tags","id":"7472"},{"type":"tags","id":"11401"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25716"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80759"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is correct regarding the lateral muscles of the foot?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Innervated by the deep peroneal nerve","Are dorsiflexors","Act to stabilize the arches of the foot","Primarily responsible for plantarflexion","Supplied by the tibial nerve"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lateral muscles of the foot, specifically the peroneus longus and peroneus brevis, are involved in eversion and stabilization of the foot. They play a crucial role in maintaining the lateral longitudinal arch of the foot, which is essential for balance and walking on uneven surfaces and thus are responsible for \u003Cstrong\u003Estabilising the arches of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInnervated by the deep peroneal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - the lateral compartment of the leg is innervated by the superficial peroneal nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAre dorsiflexors\u003C/strong\u003E - the lateral muscles are primarily involved in eversion, not dorsiflexion, which is the function of the anterior compartment muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimarily responsible for plantarflexion \u003C/strong\u003E- while they assist in plantarflexion, their main function is eversion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupplied by the tibial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - the tibial nerve supplies the posterior compartment of the leg, not the lateral compartment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The lateral muscles of the foot are primarily involved in eversion and stabilization of the foot.","The lateral compartment of the leg, which includes the peroneus longus and brevis, is innervated by the superficial peroneal nerve.","These muscles play a role in maintaining the lateral longitudinal arch of the foot."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth,